Introduction

Above is a general example of how a neural network functions. It should take in some inputs, propagate the values down a chain of neurons, and give us an output. The number of features we want to consider from the input would determine the number of neurons we have at the start. At the output, we have the number of neurons equal to the number of outcomes we would like to predict. Backpropagation would be the key component as to how the network learns - correcting its weights and biases for each feature to order to output the correct result.

In this project, we will be analysing a banknote dataset, where we would use 4 variables to predict if the note is genuine or forged in a binary classification problem.

multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  library(grid)

  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)

  numPlots = length(plots)

  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                    ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }

 if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])

  } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))

    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))

      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}

Data processing

Neural networks work best when the input values are standardised. So, we standardise our input variables to obtain a new distribution with mean 0 and standard deviation 1.

Standardising input values speeds up the training and ensures faster convergence.

A common issue with not standardising data is saturation. Given that we would be using tanh and sigmoid functions for our activation functions, if data are not centered around zero, we would get saturation of data points, where all the data would be bunched up on the left or right of zero. This would be highly detrimental to the neural network in terms of training time, as the neural net has to figure out the mean and variances of the data on its own.

The scale() function in R allows us to standardise the inputs.

training_variables <- scale(training.set[, c(1:4)])

training_prediction <- training.set$type


test_variables <- scale(test.set[, c(1:4)])

test_prediction <- test.set$type

Neural network

Making the network structure

makelayers will allow us to construct the strucure of our neural network. input_neurons, hiddenlayer_neurons, and output_neurons will form the input layer, hidden layer, and output layer respectively. To determine the number of neurons needed for each layer, we take the dimensions of the matrices that will pass through them. input_neurons thus contain 4 neurons, since we have 4 input variables. output_neurons will contain 1 neuron. hiddenlayer_neurons will contain as many neurons as we choose later.

makelayers <- function(X, y, hidden_neurons, train=TRUE) {
  input_neurons <- dim(X)[1]
  hiddenlayer_neurons <- hidden_neurons
  output_neurons <- dim(y)[1]   
  
  size <- list("input_neurons" = input_neurons,
               "hiddenlayer_neurons" = hiddenlayer_neurons,
               "output_neurons" = output_neurons)
  
  return(size)
}

Creating starting parameters

For a 3 layer neural network, we have 2 sets of parameters, weight1 bias1 and weight2 bias2, to be adjusted as the network learns.

initializeParameters <- function(X, layer.size){

    m <- dim(data.matrix(X))[2]
    
    input_neurons <- layer.size$input_neurons
    hiddenlayer_neurons <- layer.size$hiddenlayer_neurons
    output_neurons <- layer.size$output_neurons
        
    Weight1 <- matrix(runif(hiddenlayer_neurons * input_neurons), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons, ncol = input_neurons, byrow = TRUE) * 0.01
    bias1 <- matrix(rep(0, hiddenlayer_neurons), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    Weight2 <- matrix(runif(output_neurons * hiddenlayer_neurons), nrow = output_neurons, ncol = hiddenlayer_neurons, byrow = TRUE) * 0.01
    bias2 <- matrix(rep(0, output_neurons), nrow = output_neurons)
    
    parameters <- list("Weight1" = Weight1,
                   "bias1" = bias1, 
                   "Weight2" = Weight2,
                   "bias2" = bias2)
    
    return (parameters)
}

Activation

The sigmoid function will serve as our activation function for the output layer. The tanh function will serve as our activation function for the hidden layer.

sigmoid <- function(x){
    return(1 / (1 + exp(-x)))
}

Forward propagation

For forward propagation, we follow the formula:

xi+1=F(wixi+bi+1)xi+1=F(wixi+bi+1)
where F is the activation function.

forwardPropagation <- function(X, parameters, layer.size){
    
    m <- dim(X)[2]
    hiddenlayer_neurons <- layer.size$hiddenlayer_neurons
    output_neurons <- layer.size$output_neurons
    
    Weight1 <- parameters$Weight1
    bias1 <- parameters$bias1
    Weight2 <- parameters$Weight2
    bias2 <- parameters$bias2
    
    bias1_new <- matrix(rep(bias1, m), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    bias2_new <- matrix(rep(bias2, m), nrow = output_neurons)
    
    Z1 <- Weight1 %*% X + bias1_new
    A1 <- tanh(Z1)
    Z2 <- Weight2 %*% A1 + bias2_new
    A2 <- sigmoid(Z2)
    
    cache <- list("Z1" = Z1,
                  "A1" = A1, 
                  "Z2" = Z2,
                  "A2" = A2)

    return (cache)
}

Compute cost

The cost function used will be the Binary Cross Entropy loss function:

cost=−1/N∑i=1Nyilog(y^i)+(1−yi)(log(1−y^i))cost=−1/N∑i=1Nyilog⁡(y^i)+(1−yi)(log⁡(1−y^i))
Here, yy is the true label and y^y^ is the predicted output. The findcost() function takes as arguments the input matrix X, the true labels yy and a cache. The cache is the output of the forwardpropagation earlier. To calculate the error, we use the final output A2 from the cache. This will show us how far our prediction is from the actual result.

findcost <- function(X, y, cache) {
    m <- dim(X)[2]
    A2 <- cache$A2
    logprobs <- (log(A2) * y) + (log(1-A2) * (1-y))
    cost <- -sum(logprobs/m)
    return (cost)
}

Backpropagation

For backpropagation, first we collect all the weights and biases used in the forward propagation. We then calculate the gradient between the output and the hidden layer.

The flow of backpropagation moves like this:
First we need to get the derivative of the loss function w.r.t. the weight of current layer.

dW[l]=∂L∂W[l]=1mdZ[l]A[l−1]TdW[l]=∂L∂W[l]=1mdZ[l]A[l−1]T
Then we get the derivative of the loss function w.r.t. the bias of the current layer.
dW[l]=∂L∂W[l]=1mdZ[l]A[l−1]TdW[l]=∂L∂W[l]=1mdZ[l]A[l−1]T
Then we get the derivative of the previous layer w.r.t. the matrix of the output and activation from the previous layer.
dA[l−1]=∂L∂A[l−1]=W[l]TdZ[l]dA[l−1]=∂L∂A[l−1]=W[l]TdZ[l]

backwardPropagation <- function(X, y, cache, parameters, layer.size){
    
    m <- dim(X)[2]
    
    input_neurons <- layer.size$input_neurons
    hiddenlayer_neurons <- layer.size$hiddenlayer_neurons
    output_neurons <- layer.size$output_neurons

    A2 <- cache$A2
    A1 <- cache$A1
    Weight2 <- parameters$Weight2
#Last layer first
    dZ2 <- A2 - y #output layer no need diff
    dWeight2 <- 1/m * (dZ2 %*% t(A1)) 
    dbias2 <- matrix(1/m * sum(dZ2), nrow = output_neurons)
    dbias2_new <- matrix(rep(dbias2, m), nrow = output_neurons)
#Hidden layer next    
    dZ1 <- (t(Weight2) %*% dZ2) * (1 - A1^4)
    dWeight1 <- 1/m * (dZ1 %*% t(X))
    dbias1 <- matrix(1/m * sum(dZ1), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    dbias1_new <- matrix(rep(dbias1, m), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    
    gradients <- list("dWeight1" = dWeight1, 
                  "dbias1" = dbias1,
                  "dWeight2" = dWeight2,
                  "dbias2" = dbias2)
    
    return(gradients)
}

Updating parameters

Using the new gradients found by backpropagation we can calculate the amount by which we should adjust our weights and biases accordingly to eventually reduce our error as we repeat the process. The weight and bias adjustments can also be altered by changing the learning rate of network.

Wi=Wi−α∂E∂WiWi=Wi−α∂E∂Wi
Following this formula, we update the weights using the current weight, minus the learning rate (alpha) times the gradient. Because we what to reduce the loss, we have have to minus the gradient, since the gradient indicates the direction of higher cost.

To optimise the bias, we take the partial with respect to b.

bi=bi−αδibi=bi−αδi
We also minus the gradient in the same manner to reduce the cost. The learning rate in both of these equations allow us to scale the amount by which the gradient is deducted. This is important as a model that moves too aggressively can sometimes overshoot our optimal value.

updateParameters <- function(gradients, parameters, learning_rate){

    Weight1 <- parameters$Weight1
    bias1 <- parameters$bias1
    Weight2 <- parameters$Weight2
    bias2 <- parameters$bias2
    
    dWeight1 <- gradients$dWeight1
    dbias1 <- gradients$dbias1
    dWeight2 <- gradients$dWeight2
    dbias2 <- gradients$dbias2
    
    
    Weight1 <- Weight1 - learning_rate * dWeight1
    bias1 <- bias1 - learning_rate * dbias1
    Weight2 <- Weight2 - learning_rate * dWeight2
    bias2 <- bias2 - learning_rate * dbias2
    
    updated_parameters <- list("Weight1" = Weight1,
                           "bias1" = bias1,
                           "Weight2" = Weight2,
                           "bias2" = bias2)
    
    return (updated_parameters)
}

Neural network algorithm

Before starting the process of learning, we initialise the network by calling layer.size to create our 3 layers with the required neurons. We also add an additional list cost_history so we can see how our cost changes as epochs pass. Then we need to loop the following processes:
1. Forwardpropagation 2. Loss calculation 3. Find gradients 4. Update weights and bias 5. Back to step 1 for as many times as we need

Neural.net <- function(X, y, iterations, hidden_neurons, lr){
    
    layer.size <- makelayers(X, y, hidden_neurons)
    init_parameters <- initializeParameters(X, layer.size)
    cost_history <- c()
    for (i in 1:iterations) {
        forward_prop <- forwardPropagation(X, init_parameters, layer.size)
        cost <- findcost(X, y, forward_prop)
        back_prop <- backwardPropagation(X, y, forward_prop, init_parameters, layer.size)
        update_parameters <- updateParameters(back_prop, init_parameters, learning_rate = lr)
        init_parameters <- update_parameters
        cost_history <- c(cost_history, cost)
        
        if (i %% 100 == 0) cat("Iteration", i, " | Cost: ", cost, "\n")
    }
    
    model_out <- list("updated_parameters" = update_parameters,
                      "cost_hist" = cost_history)
    return (model_out)
}

Testing our neural net

Taking our finalised weights and biases, we propagate the test.set through the network and we get our predicted outcomes for each observation.

makePrediction <- function(X, y, hidden_neurons){
    layer.size <- makelayers(X, y, hidden_neurons)
    parameters <- createNN$updated_parameters
    forward_prop <- forwardPropagation(X, parameters, layer.size)
    pred <- forward_prop$A2
    
    return (pred)
}

Accuracy metrics

Precision checks for false positives in our positive predictions.

Precision=TruePositiveTruePositive+FalsePositivePrecision=TruePositiveTruePositive+FalsePositive
Recall checks for false negatives in our positive predictions.
Recall=TruePositiveTruePositive+FalseNegativeRecall=TruePositiveTruePositive+FalseNegative
F1 score is the harmonic mean of recall and precision.
F1Score=2×Precision×RecallPrecision+RecallF1Score=2×Precision×RecallPrecision+Recall
Accuracy is the percentage of correct predictions made.
Accuracy=TruePositive+TrueNegativeTruePositive+FalsePositive+TrueNegative+FalseNegativeAccuracy=TruePositive+TrueNegativeTruePositive+FalsePositive+TrueNegative+FalseNegative

calculate_stats <- function(tb, model_name) {
  acc <- (tb[1] + tb[4])/(tb[1] + tb[2] + tb[3] + tb[4])
  recall <- tb[4]/(tb[4] + tb[2])
  precision <- tb[4]/(tb[4] + tb[3])
  f1 <- 2 * ((precision * recall) / (precision + recall))
  
  cat(model_name, ": \n")
  cat("\tAccuracy = ", acc*100, "%.")
  cat("\n\tPrecision = ", precision*100, "%.")
  cat("\n\tRecall = ", recall*100, "%.")
  cat("\n\tF1 Score = ", f1*100, "%.\n\n")
}

Conclusion

Looking at the final results we can see that we achieved a very high accuracy on our model. We scored high on precision, where we only made one false positive error. A recall of 100% means that our model does not make any false negative predictions.

Overall, our model proves that machines are very capable of differentiating fake notes from genuine ones without error very quickly. This means that forgers will not be able to deposit their forged monies in banks if all notes were to be screened by machines.

Neural network

Making the network structure

makelayers <- function(X, y, hidden_neurons, train=TRUE) {
  input_neurons <- dim(X)[1]
  hiddenlayer_neurons <- hidden_neurons
  output_neurons <- dim(y)[1]   
  
  size <- list("input_neurons" = input_neurons,
               "hiddenlayer_neurons" = hiddenlayer_neurons,
               "output_neurons" = output_neurons)
  
  return(size)
}

Creating starting parameters

For a 3 layer neural network, we have 2 sets of parameters, weight1 bias1 and weight2 bias2, to be adjusted as the network learns.

initializeParameters <- function(X, layer.size){

    m <- dim(data.matrix(X))[2]
    
    input_neurons <- layer.size$input_neurons
    hiddenlayer_neurons <- layer.size$hiddenlayer_neurons
    output_neurons <- layer.size$output_neurons
        
    Weight1 <- matrix(runif(hiddenlayer_neurons * input_neurons), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons, ncol = input_neurons, byrow = TRUE) * 0.01
    bias1 <- matrix(rep(0, hiddenlayer_neurons), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    Weight2 <- matrix(runif(output_neurons * hiddenlayer_neurons), nrow = output_neurons, ncol = hiddenlayer_neurons, byrow = TRUE) * 0.01
    bias2 <- matrix(rep(0, output_neurons), nrow = output_neurons)
    
    parameters <- list("Weight1" = Weight1,
                   "bias1" = bias1, 
                   "Weight2" = Weight2,
                   "bias2" = bias2)
    
    return (parameters)
}

Activation

The sigmoid function will serve as our activation function for the output layer. The tanh function will serve as our activation function for the hidden layer.

sigmoid <- function(x){
    return(1 / (1 + exp(-x)))
}

Forward propagation

forwardPropagation <- function(X, parameters, layer.size){
    
    m <- dim(X)[2]
    hiddenlayer_neurons <- layer.size$hiddenlayer_neurons
    output_neurons <- layer.size$output_neurons
    
    Weight1 <- parameters$Weight1
    bias1 <- parameters$bias1
    Weight2 <- parameters$Weight2
    bias2 <- parameters$bias2
    
    bias1_new <- matrix(rep(bias1, m), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    bias2_new <- matrix(rep(bias2, m), nrow = output_neurons)
    
    Z1 <- Weight1 %*% X + bias1_new
    A1 <- tanh(Z1)
    Z2 <- Weight2 %*% A1 + bias2_new
    A2 <- sigmoid(Z2)
    
    cache <- list("Z1" = Z1,
                  "A1" = A1, 
                  "Z2" = Z2,
                  "A2" = A2)

    return (cache)
}

Compute cost

findcost <- function(X, y, cache) {
    m <- dim(X)[2]
    A2 <- cache$A2
    logprobs <- (log(A2) * y) + (log(1-A2) * (1-y))
    cost <- -sum(logprobs/m)
    return (cost)
}

Backpropagation

backwardPropagation <- function(X, y, cache, parameters, layer.size){
    
    m <- dim(X)[2]
    
    input_neurons <- layer.size$input_neurons
    hiddenlayer_neurons <- layer.size$hiddenlayer_neurons
    output_neurons <- layer.size$output_neurons

    A2 <- cache$A2
    A1 <- cache$A1
    Weight2 <- parameters$Weight2

    dZ2 <- A2 - y
    dWeight2 <- 1/m * (dZ2 %*% t(A1)) 
    dbias2 <- matrix(1/m * sum(dZ2), nrow = output_neurons)
    dbias2_new <- matrix(rep(dbias2, m), nrow = output_neurons)
    
    dZ1 <- (t(Weight2) %*% dZ2) * (1 - A1^2)
    dWeight1 <- 1/m * (dZ1 %*% t(X))
    dbias1 <- matrix(1/m * sum(dZ1), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    dbias1_new <- matrix(rep(dbias1, m), nrow = hiddenlayer_neurons)
    
    gradients <- list("dWeight1" = dWeight1, 
                  "dbias1" = dbias1,
                  "dWeight2" = dWeight2,
                  "dbias2" = dbias2)
    
    return(gradients)
}

Updating parameters

updateParameters <- function(gradients, parameters, learning_rate){

    Weight1 <- parameters$Weight1
    bias1 <- parameters$bias1
    Weight2 <- parameters$Weight2
    bias2 <- parameters$bias2
    
    dWeight1 <- gradients$dWeight1
    dbias1 <- gradients$dbias1
    dWeight2 <- gradients$dWeight2
    dbias2 <- gradients$dbias2
    
    
    Weight1 <- Weight1 - learning_rate * dWeight1
    bias1 <- bias1 - learning_rate * dbias1
    Weight2 <- Weight2 - learning_rate * dWeight2
    bias2 <- bias2 - learning_rate * dbias2
    
    updated_parameters <- list("Weight1" = Weight1,
                           "bias1" = bias1,
                           "Weight2" = Weight2,
                           "bias2" = bias2)
    
    return (updated_parameters)
}

Neural network algorithm

Neural.net <- function(X, y, iterations, hidden_neurons, lr){
    
    layer.size <- makelayers(X, y, hidden_neurons)
    init_parameters <- initializeParameters(X, layer.size)
    cost_history <- c()
    for (i in 1:iterations) {
        forward_prop <- forwardPropagation(X, init_parameters, layer.size)
        cost <- findcost(X, y, forward_prop)
        back_prop <- backwardPropagation(X, y, forward_prop, init_parameters, layer.size)
        update_parameters <- updateParameters(back_prop, init_parameters, learning_rate = lr)
        init_parameters <- update_parameters
        cost_history <- c(cost_history, cost)
        
        if (i %% 10000 == 0) cat("Iteration", i, " | Cost: ", cost, "\n")
    }
    
    model_out <- list("updated_parameters" = update_parameters,
                      "cost_hist" = cost_history)
    return (model_out)
}

Accuracy metrics

calculate_stats <- function(tb, model_name) {
  acc <- (tb[1] + tb[4])/(tb[1] + tb[2] + tb[3] + tb[4])
  recall <- tb[4]/(tb[4] + tb[2])
  precision <- tb[4]/(tb[4] + tb[3])
  f1 <- 2 * ((precision * recall) / (precision + recall))
  
  cat(model_name, ": \n")
  cat("\tAccuracy = ", acc*100, "%.")
  cat("\n\tPrecision = ", precision*100, "%.")
  cat("\n\tRecall = ", recall*100, "%.")
  cat("\n\tF1 Score = ", f1*100, "%.\n\n")
}

Conclusion

We see a much larger disparity in quality of predictions under this dataset in comparison to the banknote dataset. The false negative rates appear much higher (low recall) while false positives are relatively low (higher precision). This lower prediction accuracies could be due in part to much more missing data. Variables slope, ca, and thal were unusable due to large amounts of missing data. There were also missing data in other rows which were also removed as a row entirely. Small data set, combined with complexity from the number of factors leading to heart disease, makes it much harder to predict accurately. The banknotes dataset on the other hand, had much more observations (1372 total) to calibrate the network while this heart disease dataset only had a total of 294 observations.

To effectively train our neural network on this dataset, we found that we had to increase the size of the training set (80%). Testing it on the same 50/50 split used on the banknote dataset, we got a significantly poorer result of around 70 to 80% accuracy, with recall going as low as 65%.

Lowering the learning rate (0.7 to 0.6) and increasing the number of epochs(10000 to 100000) was also found to increase our predictive capabilities significantly. Too high of a learning rate can result in too big of an adjustment in weights and biases, resulting in the neural net overshooting the optimum value. To compensate for the lower rate of learning, increasing the epochs seemed to provide the neural net sufficient time to converge.

From this project, we discovered the importance of datasets when using neural networks to predict outcomes. Based on the dataset, we can expect certain levels of effectiveness and ineffectiveness a neural network can bring. Although this was a very simple network - 2 outcomes, single layer - we have shown that a simple neural network can effectively reduce human cost. i.e., Machines can move through large amounts of data while maintaining a high level of accuracy in predictions. In fact, heart failure has a 16.1% to 68.5% rate of misdiagnosis by doctors (Chun, 2021). With this statistic in mind, it might be reasonable to claim that machines can do a better job than doctors, given that the necessary health data were collected.
